section.p:
Returns the result of a bitwise AND operation performed on two integer values, for
                example:SELECT BitAND(3,6);

results: [
   "$1": 2
]

section.codeblock:
SELECT BitCLEAR(6,1);

results: [
   "$1": 6
]

SELECT BitCLEAR(6,[1,2]);

results: [
   "$1": 4
]

section.p:
Returns the results of a bitwise logical NOT operation performed on one integer
                value, for
                example:SELECT BitNOT(3);

results: [
   "$1": -4
]

Returns the result of a bitwise OR operation performed on two integer values, for
                example:SELECT BitOR(3,6);

results: [
   "$1": 7
]

Specifying a negative or zero bit position does not result in any change to the
                value. If the bit is already set, then it stays set. Specifying a negative or
                    zero position makes the function return a
                null.SELECT BitSET(6,1);

results: [
   "$1": 7
]

SELECT BitSET(6,[1,2]);

results: [
   "$1": 7
]

SELECT BitSET(6,[1,4]);

results: [
   "$1": 15
]

Example 1: left
                    shift.SELECT BitSHIFT(6,1,FALSE);

results: [
   "$1": 12
]Example
                    2: right
                shift.SELECT BitSHIFT(6,-2);

results: [
   "$1": 1
]

For
                example,SELECT IsBitSET(6,1);

results: [
   "$1": FALSE
]

SELECT BitTest(1,[1,2],FALSE);

results: [
   "$1": TRUE

SELECT IsBitSET(6,[2,3],TRUE);

results: [
   "$1": TRUE
]
